  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT179-kilavi">pakal varuvāṉai iravukkuṟi nērntāḷ pōṉṟu varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Inquired about marriage, as she seemed to grant night trysts, from him who comes at midday.</p>
          </div>


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT179">
<l>                kalleṉ kāṉattuk kaṭamā vāṭṭi</l>
<l>                yellu melliṉṟu ñamaliyu miḷaittaṉa</l>
<l>                cella laiya vutuvem mūrē</l>
<l>                yōṅkuvarai yaṭukkattut tīntēṉ kiḻitta</l>
<l>                kuvaiyuṭaip pacuṅkaḻai tiṉṟa kayavāyp</l>
<l>                pētai yāṉai cuvaitta</l>
<l>                kūḻai mūṅkiṟ kuvaṭṭiṭai yatuvē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
           <l>Having chased the wild cow in the rustling<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kalleṉa</term>: this expression is supposed to be an ideophone, but, once again, what are the associations? TVG connects it with the various sounds made by the animals of the forest.</note> forest,</l>
           <l>light is light no more and the dogs are tired.<note place="foot">The double <term xml:lang="ta">–um</term> in the second line is probably best understood as an asyndetical coordination.</note></l>
           <l>Don't go, sir; just there [is] our village!</l>
           <l>Over there on the peak [is only] short bamboo,</l>
           <l rend="indent">tasted by the foolish elephant</l>
           <l rend="indent">with deep mouth who had eaten green bamboo in heaps</l>
           <l rend="indent">that had torn sweet honey from the side of the high mountain.<note place="foot">The connection of this line with the rest is not wholly clear. If it were the elephant that had not only eaten bamboo but also torn the honey[combs], one would expect an absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">kiḻittu</term>. TVG sees <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻai</term> as the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">kiḻitta</term>, which is syntactically more likely. That would mean, the high bamboo stems (probably moved by the wind) are full of honey and thus presumably the more delicious to the elephant.</note></l>
           <lg type="alternate" resp="#TVG" sameAs="3+7b">
            <l>Our village there</l>
            <l>is a place on the peak with short bamboo...</l>
           </lg>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
